BEGIN;

INSERT INTO meetings
    (pmg_meeting_id, committee_name, committee_id, date, title,
     summary_clean, pmg_url, num_documents)
VALUES
    (39465, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-09-11', 'State of Gender Transformation at Tertiary Institutions 2023/24: CGE Briefing; with Deputy Minister', 'Video In a virtual meeting, the Committee received a briefing from the Commission for Gender Equality (CGE, Commission) on the report into employment equity and transformation in the higher education sector. The 2023/24 annual performance plan requires the Commission to proceed further with transformation hearings with a focus on tertiary institutions to assess the vulnerabilities and risks experienced by women and men at the institutions of higher learning – both as employees and students; the general level of compliance by employers with obligations flowing from specific provisions in labour legislation aimed at promoting equality or affirming the rights of women, men, and gender equality; and legislative and policy gaps and shortcomings. The Committee were briefed on transformation hearings at four universities: Walter Sisulu University, Sefako Makgatho Health Sciences University, University of Fort Hare, and University of the Western Cape. The Committee heard that the universities were advised to improve recruitment of women and persons with disabilities in academic, top and senior management positions to achieve equal representation in accordance with the Employment Equity Act. The Commission found that some universities are reluctant to review their sexual harassment policies to be in line with the Code of Good Practice 2022. A reluctance to review policies subject staff and students to lesser protective measures than the law provides and deprives them of the benefits and protection of the law. Members sought more information on race representation in top management positions and in university councils. Members also raised questions about consequent management and the Commission''s powers to enforce its recommendations. A Member said it was worrying that some institutions only implemented safety initiatives upon intervention by the Commission', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39465/', 0),
    (39517, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-09-18', 'DHET Q4 2023/24 Performance & Q1 2024/25 Performance; State of governance at UCT, With Deputy Minister', 'The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education and Training (DHET) met with the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) to receive a briefing on the Department’s 2023/24 fourth quarter & 2024/25 first quarter expenditure and performance reports. The Committee expressed its concern over the gloomy situation in the country’s higher education sector. Several universities have been and were close to being placed under administration. The governance instability of UCT was of particular concern to the Committee. The Committee indicated that higher learning institutions should be held accountable since they are funded by tax-payers’ money. Whistle-blowers who exposed governance issues in those institutions should not be intimidated at work. During the discussion, the Committee enquired about a number of issues. Those included the progress on the NQF Amendment bill, the need to change the CET Act, the Department’s 9.9 percent vacancy rate, GBV as a challenge to the Department, the support that is given to TVET graduates to start up a business, benchmarking South Africa’s TVET practices against global practices, the implementation of infrastructure projects, the consequence management measures taken against the perpetrators who incurred fruitless and wasteful expenditure, funding for persons with disabilities at TVET colleges, the recruitment process for a regional KZN TVET college manager, etc. The Committee was concerned that the Department’s expenditure and performance were not aligned. Although public funds have been spent on projects, there is no notable impact on the ground. The Committee pointed out why there is an upward trend in spending but no improvement in the Department’s actual performance. It emphasised the importance of impact of the Department’s work. The Committee was concerned with the condescending manner that it continued to receive from university professionals and urged the Department to assist it in holding university councils accountable. It ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39517/', 0),
    (39580, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-10-09', 'Higher Education Portfolio Audit Outcomes; DHET & Services SETA 2023/24 Annual Report', 'Video Services Sector Education and Training Authority (Services SETA) Report of the meeting to follow.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39580/', 0),
    (39596, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-10-10', 'QCTO & CHE 2023/24 Annual Reports; CHE briefing on remuneration of Vice-Chancellors and other senior university executives', 'Video Quality Council for Trades and Occupation (QCTO) Council on Higher Education (CHE) The Portfolio Committee convened in Parliament to receive a briefing from the Quality Council for Trades and Occupations (QCTO) and the Council on Higher Education (CHE) on their annual reports for the 2023/24 financial year. The CHE also briefed the Committee on the remuneration of Vice-Chancellors and other senior management executives of universities in South Africa. The QCTO described its unique position in the post-school education and training sector, tasked with developing and managing occupational qualifications and skills programs to meet economic demands. While it reported no underperformance, several strategies were outlined to meet targets for its five-year strategic planning cycle, including the deregistration of outdated qualifications and the development of new ones. It confirmed the approval from National Treasury to carry over accumulated surpluses for purchasing an office building. It reported that the organisation had maintained a clean audit record for eight consecutive years, with no significant findings regarding financial statements, compliance, or internal controls. The CHE presented its 2023/24 annual report, emphasising the organisation''s accomplishments concerning its non-financial performance indicators. It received a clean audit for the financial year. It released several significant publications, including a research report focusing on the success of students from previously disadvantaged backgrounds, and another analysing the trends in post-graduate programmes in South Africa from 2005 to 2020. The CHE provided insights into its financial performance for the year, reporting that revenue from exchange transactions had surpassed the budget, largely due to increased processed accreditation applications and fees from private higher education institutions for audits. Employee costs had been underspent due to delays in filling seven funded vacant positio', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39596/', 0),
    (39607, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-10-11', 'Northern Cape Urban TVET 2023/24 Annual Report', 'Video The Committee met in Parliament to engage the Northern Cape Urban TVET (NCUTVET) College on its 2023/24 annual report. Its Student Representative Council (SRC) was present, and a polished and clean account of students'' experiences at NCUTVET was submitted. Members found that presentation underwhelming and noted that it failed to accurately reflect student experiences at that institution. The collective labour union shared a “disappointing” report with the Committee. It stated that during the first term of 2019, the institution experienced a shutdown, with no teaching and learning taking place. The issues began less than three weeks after Mr. Thamsanqa Madalane took over as the principal. The union accused the institution''s leadership of nepotism, holding consecutive terms of office, misappropriation and inaccurate reporting of funds. It also criticised the institution for spending R12 million on an entrance while students were reportedly resorting to exchanging their bodies to pay for rent in their student accommodation. Additionally, the union accused the leadership of failing to implement the institution’s policies. Members did not welcome the institution''s report, and felt that it was misleading and did not reflect the reality on the ground. Members lambasted the NCUTVET for sending its report late. There was also a general consensus to place the institution under administration, but it was recommended that the Minister first install an independent assessor to further investigate the matters reported by the Auditor General of South Africa (AGSA). AGSA has opened a case with the Directorate of Priority Crimes and Investigations (DPCI) for suspected fraud. AGSA also struggled with cooperation with the management of the institution during the audit process. Members were not pleased about the AGSA’s findings at all. The institution also has too many acting positions. Members marvelled at the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) and enquired why R5', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39607/', 0),
    (39651, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-10-16', 'NSF, SAQA, SASSETA & MERSETA 2023/24 Annual Reports', 'Manufacturing, Engineering and Related Services Sector Education and Training Authority (MERSETA) National Skills Fund Safety and Security Sector Education and Training Authority (SASSETA) Report of the meeting to follow.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39651/', 0),
    (39705, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-10-23', 'Progress in implementing Post-Provisioning Norms in the TVET sector; filling of the Council Members, Principals and executive management vacant posts; Committee’s BRR report, with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Committee met virtually to receive an update from the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) on implementing the Post-Provisioning Norms (PPN) in the Technical Vocational Education and Training (TVET) sector, including filling council vacancies and others. The PPN project began in December 2014, when the Human Resource team of the South African Institute of Chartered Accountants (SAICA) was tasked with researching and preparing for the TVET PPN, which was set for implementation in April 2015. In November 2015, the Corporate Services and TVET branches combined their PPN research efforts. By February 2016, a PPN Task Team was established by the Deputy Director-General of Corporate Services. In November 2018, the Task and Resource Teams membership was expanded to include international and domestic research on PPN. The PPN model and functional structure received approval in December 2019, alongside a budget increase for the Compensation of Employees, with PPN implementation confirmed for 1 April 2020. By November 2020, the Director-General approved the PPN policy and implementation plan. The terms of office for forty-seven TVET colleges from the 2019-2024 cohort ended in the 2023/2024 financial year. Three colleges – Central Johannesburg, Tshwane South, and Coastal – had councils appointed in 2022. Nomination advertisements were published in the City Press and Sunday Times on 9 July 2023, and again on 8 October 2023. A total of 800 nominations were received: 506 from males (63%), 289 from females (37%), and five from individuals with disabilities. Most nominations were from Africans (715), followed by Coloureds (34), Whites (27), and Indians (24). Following the selection process, the Minister recommended 235 council members for the 2024-2029 term. All but two accepted their appointments. The gender breakdown of the appointees includes 134 males (57%) and 101 females (43%). Racially, 213 (90%) are Africans, with nine each from Whites and Coloureds, ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39705/', 0),
    (39771, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-10-30', 'University of Johannesburg state of governance', 'The Committee met in Parliament to engage the University of Johannesburg on its governance, administration, and related matters. UJ highlighted its consecutive clean audits, world ranking (467 out 3000+), top five position in domestic institutions, rankings on various sustainable development goals, and being a leading institution in transformation, digital transformation, and research output. The institution has a student enrolment of 53 500 students in formal programs, with about 60% of undergraduates dependent on NSFAS support. UJ employs 4500 permanent staff (1500 academic, 3000 support). Committee members acknowledged the institution’s account of the state of affairs but were rather disappointed in the SRC’s presentation as it lacked details on student challenges. They knew this because Members are bombarded with student complaints daily. They felt that NEHAWU provided a more accurate account of what might be happening on the ground. Some Members even suggested that the institution test and implement organized labour’s recommendations. Members were deeply concerned about allegations of academic fraud involving a former employee. In a complaint written to the Chairperson a while ago, the employee stated that he was being unfairly targeted, as another lecturer in the postgraduate program committed the same act, but the institution did not pursue them. UJ responded that it had instituted a forensic investigation on the matter, and the students involved had already been removed from the graduation list. The remaining three qualifications will be revoked. The whistleblower was dismissed because they engaged in sexual relations with students in their class. Members were concerned about the reputational damage such allegations could have on the institution and felt UJ should have been more proactive in dealing with the matter. However, details would be provided in writing. Questions were asked about the reappointment of AE Switch, a service provider appointed to disbur', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39771/', 0),
    (39906, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-11-20', 'State of governance, administration and related matters at Universities of Fort Hare and Limpopo', 'Video In a marathon meeting, the Committee met with the University of Limpopo and the University of Fort Hare to discuss issues related to their governance and administration. In discussions with the University of Limpopo (UL), the Committee expressed concerns about the extended terms of the Chair of Council, Mr Pandelani Nefolovhodwe, and the Vice-Chancellor, Prof Nehemiah Mokgalong, both of whom were serving beyond the limits set by the university''s statutes. The Chair of Council defended these extensions, citing the need for stability and continuity, but the Committee questioned the legality and transparency of these decisions. Financial management was another major topic, with UL reporting a surplus of R500 million for 2023. However, the Committee scrutinised the university''s high legal fees, amounting to R14.7 million, and questioned the effectiveness of internal controls, especially in light of allegations of corruption and nepotism. The Vice-Chancellor and Chair of Council faced criticism for their handling of these issues, with the Committee emphasising the need for stricter oversight and accountability. The Committee also addressed student and staff issues, including the abrupt defunding of students by the National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS). The SRC and the National Education and Health Allied Workers Union (NEHAWU) representatives highlighted governance dysfunctionality, labour relations problems, and the impact of socio-economic challenges on academic performance. The Committee urged UL to improve its stakeholder engagement and address these systemic issues more effectively. Overall, the discussions related to UL underscored the need for UL to adhere to its statutes, enhance transparency in governance, and strengthen its financial and administrative practices. The Committee called for a more collaborative approach to resolving the university''s challenges, emphasising the importance of accountability and the well-being of students and staff. The', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39906/', 0),
    (39938, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-11-22', 'DHET 2024/25 Quarter 2 performance', 'Video The Committee convened in Parliament to receive briefings from the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) on its Quarter 2 performance report for the 2024/25 financial year. DHET had been asked to prepare a presentation on the shortcomings in the sector''s legislative provisions. However, the Committee was not satisfied with the lack of information provided. They suggested that include specific problematic provisions, their limitations, and DHET''s proposals for addressing these. Committee members criticized the Department for its lack of timely and comprehensive written responses. These were often delayed and left Members more confused. Members also criticized DHET for its inability to effectively monitor and oversee its entities. They were also puzzled that DHET assigned the critical infrastructure expenditure function for Technical and Vocational Education and Training (TVET) colleges to the National Skills Fund – an entity that struggles to report on its activities and submit its annual report. Members were frustrated by DHET’s inability to fill vacancies and its reporting of quarterly targets. The information did not provide an accurate and clear picture of how DHET addressed its vacancies. At one point DHET had over 4000 vacancies and returned R580 million to the National Treasury for funded posts. Members urged it to improve. Members questioned why the National Skills Fund (NSF) procured its ICT system through the State Information Technology Agency (SITA) rather than pursue competitive bidding in the market. NSF clarified that this approach would expedite the system''s development and that procurement of ICT systems is required to be conducted through SITA. The procured service provider will develop an ICT system linked with NSF data and project management systems, scheduling, learner performance and other crucial data.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39938/', 0),
    (39983, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-11-27', 'Briefing by the DHET, USAF, SAPCO, SAUS, SATVETSA and NFSAS on the readiness for the 2025 academic year, with Deputy Minister', 'The Committee convened at False Bay Technical Vocational Education and Training ( TVET) College''s head office to receive briefings from various stakeholders, including the Department of Higher Education and Training (Department), Universities South Africa (USAf), the South African Public Colleges Organisation (SAPCO), the South African Union of Students (SAUS), the South African Technical and Vocational Education and Training Student Association ( SATVETSA), and the National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS) on the state of readiness for the 2025 academic year. Each year, the Committee emphasised the importance of universities submitting accurate student registration and enrolment data to NSFAS at the start of the academic year to ensure proper funding decisions. During the meeting, USAf expressed concerns about NSFAS''s inadequate information and communications technology systems and the insufficient number of staff at institutions to assist students when the systems experienced issues. However, NSFAS responded that they currently had 24 servicing administrators, alongside 76 graduates who were previously funded by NSFAS, to provide additional support. Further, NSFAS assured Members that its partners would offer extra assistance to facilitate the onboarding process. Members recommended that issues stemming from the 2024 registration period should be resolved to avoid recurrence in 2025. These issues included delays in processing funding applications, the disbursement of allowances, handling appeals, and matters related to private accommodation. Additionally, NSFAS announced the termination of the pilot project and the launch of the NSFAS Accredited Student Accommodation Programme. They also stated that discussions were underway to discontinue accommodation disbursements to individual students. By 2026, all accommodation disbursements would be directed to accredited or recognised accommodation providers. The SAUS called on NSFAS to resolve the backlog of student f', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/39983/', 0),
    (40052, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2024-12-04', 'National Student Financial Aid Scheme & MERSETA 2022/23 Annual Report', 'Video NSFAS Manufacturing, Engineering and Related Services Sector Education and Training Authority (MERSETA) Report of the meeting to follow.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40052/', 0),
    (40173, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-02-05', 'Resolution to subpoena the University of Limpopo to submit outstanding responses from previous meeting', 'Video 20 Nov 2024 State of governance, administration and related matters at Universities of Fort Hare and Limpopo The Committee met virtually to consider legal advice from the Parliamentary Legal Services on the process and procedure for summoning or subpoenaing the University of Limpopo to appear before it, or to provide responses to its request for information that had remained outstanding for two months and two weeks after the institution had made a commitment to respond. Members expressed their displeasure at the University''s attitude, which they described as "arrogant," disrespectful of the Committee, and undermining the role of Parliament. It was suggested that the University needed to learn a lesson that was there for all institutions to see -- that they could not disrespect Members and run the institutions inappropriately. This negatively impacted South Africa''s youth, whose future depended on the functioning of these institutions. The Parliamentary Legal Services advised the Committee on the legislative framework, empowering it to subpoena persons, documents, or institutions to Parliament. Section 56 of the Constitution and Section 14 of the Powers and Privileges Act outlined these powers. The Committee resolved to summon the University to respond to the questions posed both orally at the meeting of 20 November 2024, and those submitted to the University in a letter dated 21 November. The Committee also resolved to request the Speaker’s concurrence as soon as possible, to ensure that the summons includes a directive for the University to respond within seven days of receiving it from the sheriff of the court.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40173/', 0),
    (40207, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-02-12', 'National Skills Fund implementation of audit action plan and response to Committee questions in relation to 2023/24 Annual Report', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education and Training convened to receive a briefing from the National Skills Fund (NSF) regarding the implementation of its audit action plan and to address concerns raised in the NSF’s 2023/24 annual report. During the session, significant issues surrounding the NSF were discussed, most notably its R3.7 billion underspending in 2023/24, as well as systemic governance failures that had hindered its performance. The Auditor-General of South Africa’s findings revealed severe shortcomings in the NSF’s financial controls, including material misstatements and non-compliance with legislation. Despite the existence of an audit action plan, it was noted that 95% of the findings were superficially addressed, and no consequence management was imposed on officials implicated in these issues. One of the most glaring examples of mismanagement was the irregular payment of R16 million to Medirwe Investments, made into a business account instead of the prescribed interest-bearing account, which violated NSF protocols. This payment highlighted broader financial oversight failures within the organisation. The leadership of the NSF came under harsh criticism during the meeting for misleading the Committee about its compliance status, and for failing to attend the briefing. The redeployment to other departments of officials implicated in the Nexus forensic report, without facing any disciplinary action, was condemned for undermining accountability. The Committee also highlighted concerns over the NSF’s internal operations, including the 37 vacant positions that further exacerbated inefficiencies, and its reliance on outdated manual processes that hindered its ability to function effectively. The delay in implementing key systems, such as the enterprise resource planning system, was also noted as a barrier to improving transparency. Project mismanagement was another major issue raised by the Committee. Examples of poor oversight included the lac', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40207/', 0),
    (40221, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-02-14', 'SIU investigations conducted in the post-school education and training sector', 'Video Report of the meeting to follow.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40221/', 0),
    (40248, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-02-19', 'Wits University: readiness for the 2025 academic year, governance, administration, teaching and learning and related matters; with the Minister', 'Video The Committee met with the Witwatersrand (Wits) University and related stakeholders to discuss the institution’s readiness for the current academic year and other related matters. The presentations highlighted Wits’ commitment to academic excellence, financial stability, and student success while addressing key challenges. The Vice-Chancellor and Council Chair emphasised rising student enrolments, financial aid efforts, and private-sector partnerships to support the "missing middle." The university remained financially stable, with a budget of R11.76 billion, but student debt and the National Student Financial Aid Scheme''s (NSFAS''s) inefficiencies remained concerns. Student services had expanded to support mental health, crisis assistance, and food security. Accommodation challenges persist, despite adding private-sector beds. Safety, gender-based harm protection, and leadership development were priorities. Research and innovation continued to grow, with investments in digital learning and artificial intelligence (AI)-driven education. The Wits SRC raised issues of financial exclusion, housing shortages, and digital access, calling for expanded financial aid, rent regulation, and mental health services. Student protests reflected frustrations over financial struggles and the criminalisation of activism. The university''s unions acknowledged constructive engagement with management, but raised concerns about budget cuts, AI in teaching, and institutional transparency. They called for better staff support, fair employment practices, and improved working conditions. The discussion focused on persistent challenges at the university, particularly regarding student debt, financial aid, accommodation, transformation, and stakeholder engagement. Concerns were raised about the institution''s lack of proactive measures to address these issues, with Members questioning why certain problems recurred annually. There were inquiries about the accreditation of student housing, t', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40248/', 0),
    (40266, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-02-21', 'Meeting with the Nelson Mandela University (NMU) and University of Mpumalanga (UMP) on readiness for the 2025 academic year (governance, administration, teaching and learning and related matters)', 'Video [Editor: An earlier version erroneously referred to Mr Monaghan instead of Mr Pather in a specific section. This has been corrected. We apologise to Mr Monaghan and the Nelson Mandela University]. The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education and Training held a meeting to assess the readiness of Nelson Mandela University (NMU) and the University of Mpumalanga (UMP) for the 2025 academic year. The engagement was part of a series of the Committee’s oversight work, focusing on governance, administration, teaching, and learning at institutions of higher learning. The Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) provided an overview of the governance structures at NMU and UMP. While NMU’s Council had one ministerial appointee vacancy, UMP had nine vacancies across various constituencies. The Committee noted concerns regarding governance irregularities at UMP, including allegations of fraud and financial mismanagement. Financial sustainability was also discussed, with NMU reporting student debt of R376 million for 2023 and UMP reporting R88 million. The Committee emphasised the need for structured interventions to manage student debt and institutional financial health. The Committee raised concerns about UMP’s handling of the Vice-Chancellor recruitment process. It questioned the Council’s decision to delay the appointment process and seek a legal opinion to justify extending the incumbent’s term. The Chairperson criticised the lack of urgency in finalising the process and warned against governance practices that could undermine institutional integrity. The Committee underscored the importance of ethical leadership in universities. It called for measures to ensure that university leadership adheres to the highest ethical standards, including the introduction of lifestyle audits for key decision-makers. The affordability of student accommodation remained a concern, with Members questioning why some university-owned residences charged fees above the National Stud', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40266/', 0),
    (40299, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-02-28', 'NSFAS disbursement, accommodation and related matters; Stakeholder engagement on recent developments in PSET sector', 'The meeting took place in Tshwane South TVET college. We are trying to obtain information and will update the record as soon as we receive it.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40299/', 0),
    (40311, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-03-05', 'Tshwane North TVET & MICT SETA state of governance, administration and related matters', 'The Committee met in Parliament with the Department of Higher Education and Training, the Media Information and Communications Technology Sector Education and Training Authority (MICT SETA) and the Tshwane North Technical and Vocational Education and Training (TVET) College, to discuss matters related to the state of governance, administration, teaching and learning. The MICT SETA reported several notable achievements, including a 94% performance rating, three consecutive clean audits, and one unqualified audit with no material misstatements or findings. However, Members expressed dissatisfaction regarding the payment of R1.6 million for subsistence and transport (S&T) and the board fees for the chairperson of the MICT SETA board. Many Members felt the amount was excessive, particularly because S&T accounted for a significant portion of this payment. In response, the SETA and the DHET provided a detailed breakdown and justification for these high costs. They attributed the expenses to the wide geographical distribution of board members and the challenges associated with holding virtual meetings. The SETA board explained that virtual meetings had proved to be unmanageable and chaotic, with instances of confidential documents being leaked to the public during meetings. The Tshwane North TVET College (TNC) presented its readiness for the 2025 academic year. Members expressed concern over three projects that were currently at a standstill, despite the fact that millions of rands had already been paid to service providers. One project had received R2.8 million, another R3 million, and a third project R416 000, but no work had been completed on any of them. They were dissatisfied with the College''s decision to purchase land intended for skills development from the City of Tshwane for R3.2 million. The College had opposed this move, arguing that it should have been able to acquire the land at no cost since it was meant for public purposes. Members questioned TNC about its ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40311/', 0),
    (40362, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-03-12', 'Briefing on progress in the appointment of new Board members for the new SETA landscape, with Minister and Deputy Minister', 'The Committee convened in Parliament with representatives from the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) and the National Skills Authority (NSA) to receive updates on the assessments of the Sector Education and Training Authority (SETA) boards, as their current terms were nearing completion. The NSA confirmed that it had conducted and finalised its assessments, while the DHET assured the Committee that the process of appointing new board members for the SETAs was in progress. Members enquired about the key assessment criteria and whether any benchmarking exercises had been undertaken. While the presentations were appreciated, Members voiced concerns about high remuneration payments and subsistence and travel (S&T) expenses associated with the SETA boards. They observed that the number of board meetings and generous remuneration packages did not align with actual performance and governance stability. SETAs that offered the highest remuneration and S&T expenses were often the ones with poor audit outcomes and subpar performance. Members recommended that the DHET explore ways to reduce costs related to board remuneration and S&T expenses. For instance, the Agri-SETA, which spent R2 million, had maintained excellent audit results consecutively. In contrast, the Services SETA, which spent just under R6.9 million, had experienced poor audit outcomes for five consecutive years. Members felt that, in many instances, a high frequency of board meetings did not translate into productivity. They also urged the Minister to inform boards that they would be subject to lifestyle audits, and they suggested tightening certain provisions in the upcoming amendments to the Skills Development Act. Additionally, members called on the DHET to address the excessive spending culture among SETAs. They expressed concern about board members who were departing after overcommitting SETAs to expenditure. However, they welcomed that a review of those decisions would be made during the ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40362/', 0),
    (40427, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-03-19', 'DHET Q3 2024/25 Performance; Overview of registration and enrolments in PSET sector for 2025; with Deputy Minister', 'The Committee met in Parliament to review the Department of Higher Education and Training''s (DHET''s) third quarter report for 2024/25, and to discuss enrolments in the post school education and training (PSET) system for 2025. Members were dissatisfied with the Department''s 58% performance, questioning its ability to meet its targets, which were criticised as lacking impact. The DHET responded by pointing out that it oversees 110 entities, excluding private institutions, and said that achieving some targets was dependent on external factors beyond its control. Members expressed significant criticism regarding the Department’s annual performance plan and its reporting on targets. Officials faced sharp scrutiny when it became evident that the Higher Education Act had not been presented to Parliament, despite repeated requests from Members for the DHET to review it, as well as the Community Education and Training Act and the Skills Development Act. The explanation offered was deemed unsatisfactory, prompting a resolution to invoke Section 17(2) of the Powers and Privileges Act. Members felt deliberately misled by the DHET, and strongly agreed to take action, as this undermined Parliament and the South African public. Following discussion, some leeway to institute consequence management against the officials responsible for misleading Parliament was granted, but the Committee would start engaging legal services if they were not satisfied with the response to instituting Section 17(2). The Department confirmed that the National Student Financial Aid Scheme had exceeded its initial funding targets, supporting 542 653 university students, which surpassed the expected 417 938 beneficiaries. Over 1.7 million students had enrolled in PSET institutions for the 2025 academic year. Members acknowledged the milestones achieved, but felt stronger interventions were needed to fast-track the filling of vacancies for the TVET colleges. The DHET was also criticised for returning funds', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40427/', 0),
    (40513, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-04-02', 'Challenges of workers in the Post-School Education and Training (PSET) sector: engagement with National Tertiary Education Union (NTEU)', 'The Committee met in Parliament to engage with the National Tertiary Education Union (NTEU) to discuss challenges faced by workers within the Post-School Education and Training (PSET) sector. NEHAWU was also invited to the deliberations but could not attend due to scheduling clashes. NTEU highlighted numerous challenges faced by workers in the sector, expressing concern that institutional autonomy—intended to promote academic freedom—has been misused by some institutions to evade accountability. Central to these challenges was the victimisation of employees, leading to a culture of fear in the workplace. Many workers feared joining a union or speaking up about their concerns. Additionally, issues such as inconsistent remuneration practices, selective and varying retirement ages, and the excessive use of part-time and contract staff, were highlighted. Furthermore, bloated executive management structures with high salary packages have adversely impacted the financial sustainability of institutions. NTEU proposed standardising university statutes and revising the Higher Education Act to include organised labour unions in governance structures. They noted that some institutions exclude these unions from councils and do not recognise them despite having members. NTEU called for standardised practices for basic rights and collective bargaining. Members acknowledged the challenges raised by the NTEU and appreciated its recommendations. They agreed with most of the inputs, leading them to criticise the Department for its failures to exercise effective oversight over its institutions. These failures in the sector were attributed to DHET''s inability to implement consequence management and act promptly against corruption and maladministration. Additionally, councils and senior managers who evaded accountability at all costs were allowed to continue despite their institutions performing poorly. Members further lambasted the DHET about its inability to hold officials accountable', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40513/', 0),
    (40594, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-04-23', 'Briefing by the Central University of Technology (CUT) on its responses to issues raised during the Committee''s oversight visit to the University', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education, Science and Innovation met with the Central University of Technology (CUT) to engage on governance, operational and stakeholder issues following its oversight visit to the University on 25 March 2025. The meeting followed an independent assessor''s investigation into CUT after the suspension of its Vice Chancellor in 2022, which led to directives for biannual reporting from August 2024 to August 2026. Stakeholders, including the National Education, Health and Allied Workers’ Union (NEHAWU), the Institutional Forum and student representatives, raised concerns over deteriorating infrastructure, inadequate stakeholder consultation and student exclusion from institutional processes. Students reported frustration over the National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS) placing over 800 students on blocked lists during the exam period and dissatisfaction with the R25 000 cap on unaccredited accommodation, forcing students into unsafe and under-resourced housing. Concerns were also raised about overcrowded lecture halls, an excessive reliance on part-time academic staff, and poor maintenance of sports grounds and toilets. NEHAWU and the Institutional Forum criticised the lack of transparency and consultation in financial decisions and procurement, including allegations of inflated property acquisitions. The Committee expressed dissatisfaction with CUT’s employment equity practices. Members criticised the appointment of a foreign national as dean in the Faculty of Engineering, Environmental, Built and Information Technology over a qualified black South African woman and noted the underrepresentation of coloured and Indian staff in academic posts. Governance failures at CUT Innovation Services (CUTIS), CUT’s third income stream entity, were scrutinised, particularly conflicts of interest with CUT executives and Council members serving on CUTIS’s interim board. The Committee also questioned the amendment of CUT’s institutional s', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40594/', 0),
    (40646, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-05-07', 'NSFAS update on student appeals, funding, allowances, accommodation and related matters', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education and Training convened to address several pressing issues affecting the National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS). The committee welcomed the recent appointment of the new NSFAS board and acknowledged the significant challenges it faces. Key areas of discussion included student appeals, funding decisions for the 2025 academic year, the disbursement of funds and allowances, the close-out report, student accommodation, and related matters. Committee members raised several concerns, particularly regarding the timing and financial impact of NSFAS decisions. A recent circular about the capping of payments for unaccredited student accommodation drew scrutiny, with members questioning who would bear the financial consequences for affected students. Further concerns were raised about communication challenges between NSFAS and higher education institutions, particularly around the exchange of registration data. These issues have adversely affected funding decisions and caused undue prejudice to students. Delays in the disbursement of allowances and payments to accommodation providers were also highlighted, with reports of financial strain on service providers due to outstanding payments. In response, NSFAS presented its strategic repositioning plan, emphasising a transition toward becoming a more proactive, efficient, and student-centred organisation.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40646/', 0),
    (40690, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-05-14', 'CETA progress in implementing Duja Forensic Report recommendations; SETA Board appointments', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education and Training received a briefing from the Construction Education and Training Authority (CETA) and the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) on the implementation of recommendations arising from the Duja Forensic Report into CETA''s affairs. The Committee expressed serious concern over the Department''s prolonged delay in releasing the R18.9 million Duja Report, which had impeded accountability for implicated individuals, some of whom were suspected of having since secured appointments elsewhere in the post-school system. Members were alarmed by findings in the Duja Report, including R738 million in discretionary grants awarded without accounting authority oversight, excessive salaries paid to executives, and the accreditation of non-compliant training providers. Other examples cited involved officials receiving millions in remuneration under questionable circumstances, including cases of forged qualifications. Despite these findings, the Department and CETA leadership failed to take timely action, with the Department’s legal unit criticised for failing to brief the Minister or ensure proper consequence management. The Committee heard that a legal firm had been hired by a previous CETA board to review and consolidate the Duja findings, raising further concerns about the recycling of implicated officials and the duplication of costly investigative efforts. Members queried the total expenditure on previous forensic reports and challenged the integrity of legal advice that may have diluted the original recommendations. It was confirmed that the Duja Report had been received by the Department in July 2023 but had not been released to the public by the time of the meeting. The meeting was repeatedly disrupted by a Member’s refusal to adhere to Committee procedure regarding SETA board appointments. After numerous warnings, the Member was ejected for refusing to direct his questions through the agreed channels. T', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40690/', 0),
    (40807, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-05-28', 'Local Government SETA allegations of corruption, maladministration and related matters;', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education convened to receive a comprehensive progress report from the Local Government Sector Education and Training Authority (LGSETA). This followed a whistleblower-triggered forensic investigation into allegations of systemic corruption, maladministration, and governance failures within the entity. Key findings from the investigation revealed significant procurement irregularities, including a R2.3 billion tender that showed non-compliance, the irregular appointment of training providers, discretionary grant allocations made without board approval, and instances of financial bias and overpayment. The report also highlighted conflicts of interest involving individuals serving on multiple procurement committees. Although a criminal case had been opened with the Hawks, LGSETA was unable to publicly disclose names due to ongoing legal proceedings. Despite governance challenges, the LGSETA reported a notable improvement in its performance, rising from 66% in 2020/21 to 80% in 2023/24. The Committee was also informed about the LGSETA''s partnership with China, which includes a training programme for 500 unemployed youth in areas such as mechatronics, artificial intelligence, and e-commerce. The programme, although fully funded, was said to have received a low application response, which then prompted a re-advertisement. The entity took precautions to ensure that there would be no political interference in the process by administering bursaries through an online portal. The total bursary target for the current financial year was said to be 1 640 students, including 700 new enrolments. Further discussions addressed the LGSETA''s role in supporting local government service delivery. Committee Members raised serious concerns regarding an unexplained reversal of a qualified audit opinion by the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA), which occurred via a phone call rather than formal communication. This raised criticism from Members, w', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40807/', 0),
    (40835, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-05-30', 'Minister of Higher Education''s withdrawal of SETA Boards Chairperson appointments; University of Limpopo matter', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education and Training met to receive a briefing from the Minister of Higher Education on the governance challenges at the University of Limpopo and the withdrawal of the previously announced appointments of chairpersons to the boards of Sector Education and Training Authorities (SETAs). On the University of Limpopo, the Minister indicated that her Department required more time to consolidate a comprehensive report. Members noted that the institution had failed to respond to a parliamentary summons and written questions dating back several months. While some supported granting the requested extension to 31 July 2025, others voiced strong objections, citing Parliament’s authority being undermined. The Committee ultimately resolved to re-serve the summons while granting the Minister the additional time to submit the report. Regarding SETA board appointments, the Minister outlined the process followed in receiving over 500 applications and appointing a panel to shortlist candidates. She withdrew the original list of appointments in response to public concerns over demographic representation and procedural transparency. The withdrawal occurred before appointment letters were issued. The Minister stated that SETA CEOs had since been appointed as interim accounting authorities in consultation with National Treasury. Members raised serious concerns about the lack of transparency in the selection process. They criticised the Minister’s refusal to disclose the identities or vetting status of the panel, questioned whether the panel was politically connected, and expressed frustration with inconsistent criteria applied to candidates. The exclusion of young people, questions over reappointing individuals previously accused of misconduct, and the absence of racial considerations in the gazette were also raised. There was widespread dissatisfaction with the Department’s handling of legal matters, particularly the conduct of senior legal off', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40835/', 0),
    (40871, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-06-04', 'Minister’s submission of SETA Boards Advisory Panel names; State of affairs at Sefako Makgatho University (with Deputy Minister)', 'Video The Committee engaged with Sefako Makgatho University in Parliament to discuss its state of affairs. As has often been the case with many institutions in the Post-School Education and Training (PSET) sector, the interaction involved the Committee criticising the university for its alleged failures in governance, executive management, and infrastructure projects. The presence of too many acting personnel in key senior management positions was a significant concern for the Committee, noting that these acting arrangements were destabilising the institution. They were particularly alarmed by the situation involving the Chief Financial Officer, who was responsible for approving payments but was also serving as the acting Deputy Vice Chancellor for operations, citing a clear conflict of interest as he was now overseeing the same projects that he processed payments for. The institution’s stakeholders had nothing positive to say about the University’s management and the council, accusing them of exclusion from critical engagements that they ought to be part of or consulted on. The SRC claimed they were deliberately excluded from critical discussions on matters that affected students. The opposing presentations between management and its stakeholders were glaring. Organised labour accused management, among others, of a serious move to privatise services at the institution. They also strongly believed that infrastructure projects were not being finished, so that some people may continue to benefit from them. They also questioned the recruitment process for the newly appointed Vice Chancellor, citing how organised labour was excluded from the process. Serious allegations were made involving the infrastructure projects, accusing management of appointing a new service provider for the 2000-bed infrastructure project without following competitive procurement processes. New contractor, Insight Construction (Pty) Ltd, was handpicked as there was no procurement process followe', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40871/', 0),
    (40946, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-06-11', 'Briefing by Ingwe TVET College on governance, administration, teaching and learning and related matters', 'Video The Committee convened in Parliament to engage the Ingwe TVET College on its state of affairs. The College experienced a myriad of challenges, as reported by its student representatives and organised labour. Most of these challenges were not new to Members as they were common across different TVET colleges in the system. Some of these issues included online registration problems, where students applying online did not receive timely notifications about their application status, risking being overlooked in favour of walk-in applicants. There was also a shortage of textbooks and the unavailability of robotics lecturers and resources, with new programmes being introduced without the provision of necessary resources for students. The stakeholders further highlighted the absence of permanent lecture halls, with many temporary structures dating back over five years, lack of chairs and desks, poorly maintained computer labs, limited Wi-Fi access on campus, restricted to administrative areas, outdated workshop equipment, with no facilities for the robotics programme, late payments of NSFAS allowances, and unsanitary toilets across the campuses. Members were appalled by the state of affairs at Ingwe especially the exposure of students and staff to unclean toilets. Members were told that students and the staff seldom had to relieve themselves outside due to the unsanitary state of the toilets at the institution. The Department was warned to take its oversight role seriously, as a lack of clean toilets was tantamount to disrespect to South Africans. Members expressed their concern that many of the challenges discussed were not new and criticised the Department for its inability to effectively hold institutions accountable. They were particularly surprised to learn that a senior official, the Deputy Principal for Corporate Services at Ingwe TVET College, was unaware of the Department''s sexual harassment policy. This revelation came during discussions about a sexual harass', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/40946/', 0),
    (41010, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-06-18', 'SETA Board Chairpersons Matter; AGSA Assessment of DHET and entities APP; DHET response to Committee’s Oversight visit reports', 'Video 2025/26 Annual Performance Plans ATC250324: Report of the Portfolio Committee on Higher Education and Training on its Oversight Visit to the North West and Gauteng Post-School Education and Training Institutions on 27 – 31 January 2025, Dated 19 March 2025 ATC250603: Report of the Portfolio Committee on Higher Education on Its Oversight visit to the Free State on 24 – 28 March 2025, Dated 28 May 2025 Members raised concerns regarding the composition and independence of the panel appointed by the Minister to recommend appointments to boards such as NSFAS, the National Skills Authority and university councils. Members raised serious concerns about the transparency, conflict of interest, and legality of the panel’s operations and called for the Minister, panel members, and departmental officials to appear before the Committee within seven days to clarify the process, provide documentation, and account for alleged misleading conduct. The Committee received a briefing from the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA) on its proactive review of the 2025/26 Annual Performance Plans (APPs) of the Department of Higher Education and Training and its entities. The AGSA identified recurring issues, including the overuse of report-based performance indicators, lack of alignment between APPs and the Medium-Term Development Plan, and unsigned Service Level Agreements SLAs) with Sector Education and Training Authorities (SETAs). It emphasised the need for SMART (Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound) indicators to enable accountability and measurable outcomes. SETAs, the National Skills Fund, and the National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS) were flagged for ongoing weaknesses, with some indicators deemed unverifiable or irrelevant to service delivery. Members expressed frustration over the Department’s failure to act on the Auditor-General’s recommendations. They criticised weak oversight, poor planning alignment, insufficient consequence management, and t', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41010/', 0),
    (41088, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-06-25', 'Department of Higher Education and Training 2025/26 Annual Performance Plan (with Minister)', '2025/26 Annual Performance Plans The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education convened to receive a presentation from the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) on its 2025–2030 Strategic Plan, the 2025/26 Annual Performance Plan (APP), and Budget. The session aimed to assess whether the Department’s planning adequately addressed systemic challenges in the Post-School Education and Training (PSET) sector, including infrastructure backlogs, NEET rates, institutional governance, and funding disparities. The Department reported a total budget of R129 billion, with 91% allocated to transfers and subsidies. University education would receive the largest share (60.1%), followed by TVET colleges (15.4%) and community education and training (2.2%). The Department noted a reduction in the number of performance indicators from 90 to 51 following Auditor-General feedback. This was intended to improve alignment with available resources and ensure SMART criteria were applied. Members raised concerns about the vagueness of several indicators and the lack of clarity on the Department’s role in achieving its targets. The Auditor-General’s office confirmed that some indicators did not meet the required standard for measurability or accountability. The credibility of the APP was questioned, and Members expressed doubt about supporting the budget in the absence of defined commitments. The Committee expressed serious concern about high youth unemployment and the persistent marginalisation of the TVET and community college sectors. Members highlighted stagnant TVET funding since 2013, the entrenched university-centric model, and the Department’s failure to reposition vocational education despite policy intent. Questions were also raised about the performance and accountability of Sector Education and Training Authorities (SETAs), with Members criticising the focus on compliance rather than outcomes. The Committee questioned the Department’s allocation of R9.7 million to Highe', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41088/', 0),
    (41159, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-07-02', 'Higher Education and Training Budget Vote Report', 'Video The Committee convened briefly to consider its report on the Department of Higher Education and Training’s Budget Vote. The Committee was scheduled to debate the report in the House on the following day. The report was adopted with no amendments.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41159/', 0),
    (41308, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-07-16', 'Briefing by the Commission for Gender Equality (CGE) on Sexual Harassment at Institutions of Higher Learning in 2024; with Deputy Minister', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education and Training met to receive a briefing from the Commission for Gender Equality (CGE) on its 2024 reports into sexual harassment and transformation at institutions of higher learning. The CGE presented two reports: one providing a broad overview, and another detailing research findings related to gender transformation and institutional responses to sexual harassment in the Post-School Education and Training (PSET) sector. The CGE’s findings revealed that many institutions lacked the capacity, systems, and commitment to address sexual harassment effectively. Common challenges included poor case management, underqualified first responders, a lack of inclusive infrastructure, and weak reporting mechanisms. Students—particularly women, members of the LGBTQI+ community, and persons with disabilities—reported reluctance to come forward due to a lack of institutional action and the continued presence of perpetrators on campuses. The Commission also raised concerns about persistent gender and racial pay disparities, notably at Stellenbosch University, and criticised the slow pace of transformation in leadership and employment equity. Members of the Committee expressed deep dissatisfaction with the limited progress in implementing the CGE’s longstanding recommendations. They criticised the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) for failing to enforce compliance, adequately monitor institutions, or respond to public and stakeholder concerns. The Department and Ministry were viewed as complicit in the worsening crisis of gender-based violence and femicide (GBVF) across the PSET sector. The CGE reported varying levels of institutional performance but noted that most institutions were quick to adopt “soft laws” while avoiding the structural reforms needed to ensure accountability and inclusion. The Commission highlighted systemic weaknesses, including the absence of standardised gender transformation policies, lack of ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41308/', 0),
    (41344, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-07-18', 'Independent panel for selection of SETA Chairpersons; with Deputy Ministers', 'Video The Committee expressed dissatisfaction with Minister Nkabane’s continued absence from meetings addressing serious concerns about the irregular appointment process of the SETA board panel members. Members viewed her conduct as undermining parliamentary authority and accountability, with some accusing her of deliberately avoiding oversight. The Director-General was also criticised for attempting to cancel meetings without authority and for failing to ensure proper departmental participation. Several Members called for both the Minister and DG to be referred to the Ethics Committee and formally summoned, alongside other individuals who had failed to respond or provided misleading communication. While some Members supported giving the Minister one final opportunity to appear, others argued that the matter had reached a point where immediate disciplinary steps were warranted. The Committee ultimately agreed to offer one last chance for the Minister to appear, with the understanding that failure to do so would result in further action. Testimonies from Mr Mabuza Ngubane and Adv Terry Motau, who were appointed as chairpersons of the selection panel, revealed that neither had been involved in the actual panel process. One was approached informally and never received meeting details, while the other was never invited to participate at all, despite receiving an official appointment letter. Both stated under oath that they had not been part of any deliberations or panel work, raising serious questions about the integrity of the process. It was further revealed that unofficial individuals, particularly someone known professionally to one of the witnesses, played a prominent role in initiating the process despite lacking any formal departmental role.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41344/', 0),
    (41357, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-07-22', 'Independent panel for selection of SETA Chairpersons', 'Video The Committee heard from several panel members and the Director General, all of whom denied active involvement in the selection or approval of the SETA Chairpersons. The Committee, questioning whether the Minister had misled Parliament about the existence of an independent panel, decided to continue with hearings despite the Minister’s dismissal. Members argued that panel members remained accountable regardless of the Minister’s departure. The panel members clarified their limited or no roles in approving the appointments, and the Director General confirmed he was aware of the process but was not involved in decision-making. The Committee found it unusual that none of the officials, all employed by the department, claimed involvement. The Committee welcomed the new Minister and Deputy Minister appointments and concluded that there was never a genuinely independent panel in the process. The controversy could have been avoided had the Minister acted transparently. Only one individual, an external legal advisor, was truly independent, while the rest were departmental officials now distancing themselves from the scandal', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41357/', 0),
    (41466, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-09-02', 'Committee Strategic Planning Workshop', 'The meeting took place in Saldanha Bay Hotel. We are trying to obtain information and will update the record as soon as we receive it.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41466/', 0),
    (41489, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-09-03', 'Committee Strategic Planning Workshop', 'The meeting took place in Saldanha Bay Hotel. We are trying to obtain information and will update the record as soon as we receive it.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41489/', 0),
    (41520, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-09-04', 'Committee Strategic Planning Workshop', 'The meeting took place in Saldanha Bay Hotel. We are trying to obtain information and will update the record as soon as we receive it.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41520/', 0),
    (41567, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-09-10', 'College of Cape Town state of affairs: with Minister', 'Video The Committee met in Parliament to interact with the College of Cape Town was termed one of the Department’s star colleges. However, the College was plagued by significant challenges within top management, with extreme factionalism between the principal of the college and deputies. It was claimed the factions had also affected the independence and integrity of its stakeholders such as the unions and the SRC. These challenges prompted the Minister to visit the college, and after engaging with the relevant parties, he had decided to constitute a stabilisation team, which would be in addition to a task team commissioned by the TVET branch of the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET). Committee members were alarmed to learn of persistent tension among senior managers, which has resulted in weak governance, low staff morale and disruptions to academic programmes. The Department did not have positive reflections about the principal, stating that the principal was facing 21 charges. There were extensive questions by Members about the charges that had been raised including the principal’s approach to staff recruitment and the selection of interns as well as the principal claiming that the DHET Director General’s activities in the college are an overreach. There were complaints about the principal referring to the College as his college and that, as he was born in Zimbabwe, he should not be occupying a job that a South African could occupy, as it was not a critical scarce skill. The Committee resolved to hold a further engagement at the College.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41567/', 0),
    (41625, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-09-17', 'DHET Q4 2024/25 and Q1 2025/26 Performance; CGE recommendations implementation', 'Video The Committee met in Parliament with the of the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) to receive briefings on its quarterly performance, and an update on the implementation of the Commission for Gender Equality (CGE) recommendations. The Department presented its Q4 2024/25 and Q1 2025/26 performance, highlighting an overall achievement rate of just over 59% despite spending nearly the full budget. While some programmes such as Community Education and Training showed stable delivery, persistent weaknesses were noted in Skills Development, infrastructure planning, and audit compliance. Committee members expressed frustration at the mismatch between expenditure and outcomes, poor consequence management, and recurring findings from the Auditor-General. The Department acknowledged difficulties with institutional autonomy, capacity constraints, and delays in critical projects but pointed to corrective measures, including tighter DDG performance contracts, ICT upgrades, and oversight mechanisms for SETAs. The Department briefed the Committee on progress in responding to the Commission for Gender Equality’s recommendations. Efforts are underway to strengthen survivor-centred policies, tackle GBV in Post-School Education and Training (PSET) institutions, and accelerate gender transformation, with the support of Higher Health, National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS) and Universities South Africa (USAf). Outreach roadshows, workshops, and new advisory roles have been introduced, alongside projects such as Men-2-Men and the Social Inclusion Review and Improvement Model (SI-RIM). However, challenges remain in institutional compliance, uneven application of sexual harassment policies, and weak accountability for transformation. The Department stressed its commitment to working with stakeholders, improving reporting systems, and building on the Minister and Deputy Minister’s leadership to drive inclusivity, student safety, and accountability in the sector.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41625/', 0),
    (41654, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-09-19', 'SETA Administrator appointment process; 2026 Academic Year readiness; with Minister', 'Video Minister’s Statement on 2026 Academic Year Minister''s Statement on SETA Adminstrator Appointments Department Statement on SETA Administrator Appointments The Portfolio Committee met with the Department to scrutinise why three Sector Education and Training Authority (SETA) had been placed under administration. Committee members sought clarity on the rationale for placing the Construction SETA, Local Government SETA, and Services SETA under administration, highlighting concerns over the delayed implementation of previous forensic reports and systemic governance failures. Some Members strongly questioned the calibre and integrity of the appointed administrators. The Minister and the Department explained that the interventions were necessary to stabilize the institutions, address allegations of misconduct by CEOs and the accounting authorities, and ensure proper oversight, noting that these measures were not punitive but aimed at institutional stability and adherence to statutory frameworks. Questions were raised about the role and accountability of the Director General, the consistency of information provided on forensic reports such as the Duja Report, and the processes followed in appointing administrators. The Committee was also briefed by the National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS) and the Department on the 2026 academic year state of readiness, including student applications, funding, and accommodation. The Department reported ongoing engagement with universities and TVET colleges to manage student placements, with an emphasis on prioritizing student needs in consultation with staff and stakeholders. Members welcomed the announcement of an additional R13 billion in NSFAS funding, which was expected to alleviate some of the funding challenges, but expressed concern over prior mismanagement and delays in fund disbursement. Questions were raised about whether funding would reach students equitably, and Members stressed the need for timely payments to prev', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41654/', 0),
    (41771, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-10-15', 'Higher Education Portfolio Audit Outcomes; DHET 2024/25 Annual Report (with Minister)', 'Video Annual Reports 2024/25 The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education met in Parliament to receive briefings from the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA) on the 2024/25 audit outcomes of the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) and its entities, as well as a presentation from the Department on its 2024/25 Annual Report. The AGSA’s consolidated audit results indicated a mixed performance across the post-school education and training (PSET) sector. While certain improvements were recorded, systemic weaknesses persisted, particularly in governance, compliance, and performance reporting. Of the 26 public universities, 15 achieved clean audits, while nine obtained unqualified audit opinions with findings—reflecting recurring weaknesses in management controls and slow implementation of audit recommendations. The AGSA reported that several institutions, including UNISA, Mangosuthu University of Technology (MUT), Tshwane University of Technology (TUT), and the University of Fort Hare (UFH), failed to submit their financial statements on time, undermining accountability and transparency. The number of clean audits declined from 17 to 15, signalling stagnation in governance and oversight effectiveness. Audit outcomes for Technical and Vocational Education and Training (TVET) colleges showed moderate improvement, with 12 colleges achieving clean audits compared to five in the previous cycle. However, the AGSA noted that nearly half of the colleges still relied on auditors to correct accounting errors—an indication of weak internal controls, inadequate record keeping, and persistent compliance lapses, particularly in procurement and financial reporting. Community Education and Training (CET) colleges demonstrated stronger control environments, with six of nine institutions achieving clean audits. Two colleges received qualified opinions, and one failed to submit on time. The AGSA commended CET colleges for improved financial management but cautioned that qua', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41771/', 0),
    (41797, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-10-17', 'South African Qualifications Authority (SAQA), Quality Council for Trades and Occupations (QCTO) and Council on Higher Education (CHE) 2024/25 Annual Reports', 'Video Annual Reports 2024/25 The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education met to receive briefings on the 2024/25 Annual Reports from the South African Qualifications Authority (SAQA), the Quality Council for Trades and Occupations (QCTO), and the Council on Higher Education (CHE). All three entities reported clean audits and strong performance against their targets but highlighted significant underfunding relative to their expanding mandates. SAQA presented Project Phoenix, a digital verification platform, as an innovative measure to combat qualification fraud. The QCTO indicated that it received less than half of its requested budget, which constrained its operations, and committed to providing detailed written data on compliance by Technical and Vocational Education and Training (TVET) colleges. The CHE highlighted that it was executing an unfunded transformation oversight mandate. The Chairperson questioned why government departments relied on private verification services instead of SAQA, noting that this practice undermined the entity and wasted public resources. Members expressed concern about graduate unemployment and whether accredited courses were responsive to labour market needs. The Committee also criticised the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) for inadequate oversight of universities, citing high legal costs at the University of Limpopo and delays in resolving certification backlogs in some SETAs. The Committee requested a written report from the DHET on the status of SETA and Community Education and Training (CET) reforms. It noted the funding constraints and oversight gaps highlighted by the entities and emphasised the need for closer alignment of education with labour market requirements. The Chairperson urged the Minister to support and fund SAQA’s Project Phoenix to enable free verification for unemployed graduates and to consider elevating it to a national programme.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41797/', 0),
    (41903, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-10-29', 'MERSETA and the Construction SETA (CETA) 2024/25 annual reports', 'Video Annual Reports 2024/25 The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education met with the Manufacturing, Engineering and Related Services SETA (MERSETA) and the Construction SETA (CETA) to engage on their 2024/25 Annual Reports. The meeting was dominated by severe concerns over departmental accountability and systemic governance failures within the entities. The Committee formally rejected the apology submitted by the Director-General (DG) for his absence, citing a pattern of non-attendance at oversight meetings. Members expressed a collective loss of confidence in the DG’s administrative ability to manage the Department and its entities, resolving to formally escalate the matter. Both SETAs presented qualified audit opinions from the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA) for the fourth (CETA) and third (MERSETA) consecutive years. CETA’s financial management was scrutinised for R871.4 million in cumulative irregular expenditure and a lack of audit evidence for R2.7 billion in discretionary grant commitments. MERSETA faced criticism for holding R5.3 billion in financial reserves while failing to fully execute its skills development mandate. The discussion revealed allegations of officials misleading the Committee, the systematic victimisation of whistleblowers at CETA, and a failure by the Department to implement a central Learner Management System (LMS) despite repeated AGSA recommendations. The appointment process for SETA CEOs was also questioned, with Members alleging that recent five-year appointments circumvented the mandatory national recruitment process. The Committee concluded with strict resolutions, including a deadline for CETA to submit documents and an intention to pursue legislative reforms. Members also agreed to hold a dedicated follow-up meeting on the National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS) accommodation cap.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41903/', 0),
    (41976, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-11-05', 'Follow-up: College of Cape Town state of governance, administration and related matters', 'Report of the meeting to follow.', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/41976/', 0),
    (42044, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-11-12', 'Sol Plaatjie University state of governance, administration and related matters (with Deputy Minister)', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education met physically with Sol Plaatje University (SPU) to engage on matters relating to governance, administration, student welfare, and institutional effectiveness. The meeting took place within the broader context of systemic challenges facing the Post-School Education and Training (PSET) sector, including governance deficiencies, gender-based violence (GBV), and financial instability associated with the National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS). The Committee sought clarity on SPU’s institutional culture, student accommodation environment, and disciplinary processes. In line with its oversight mandate, the Committee examined SPU’s governance practices, financial management, and preparedness for the 2026 academic year. Members also expressed concern over the Department of Higher Education and Training’s (DHET) repeated failures to respond to correspondence and attend scheduled meetings, describing this as a breakdown in accountability. SPU reported several achievements, including consecutive unqualified audits, infrastructure investments exceeding R3 billion, and an increase in enrolment to 7 182 students. The University highlighted strategic growth areas, including health sciences, mining, information and communication technology, and expanded research capacity. Members raised a number of serious concerns. The Student Representative Council (SRC) highlighted unsafe and exploitative accommodation conditions, delayed NSFAS disbursements, and debt-related exclusion practices. Organised labour drew attention to inadequate employee benefits, continued outsourcing despite previous insourcing commitments, and governance gaps such as the absence of a Legal Directorate. The Institutional Forum (IF) reported persistent gender disparities in senior academic positions and weaknesses in the university’s policy review cycles. Concerns were also raised about SPU’s handling of GBV matters. Members noted cases in which victims appea', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42044/', 0),
    (42088, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-11-19', 'Walter Sisulu University (WSU) on its state of governance, administration, teaching and learning', 'Video The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education met with the Walter Sisulu University (WSU), the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET), the National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS), and university stakeholders to assess the state of governance, administration, teaching and learning, and institutional stability at WSU, and to evaluate whether reported reform measures were improving conditions for students and staff. The Department noted the University''s historical context and reported measurable progress, including stabilised leadership and unqualified audits, while flagging ongoing risks such as governance representation and internal control weaknesses. It highlighted serious campus incidents and the institution''s responsive actions, while acknowledging strong academic outcomes and infrastructure investment against a backdrop of severe accommodation shortages. WSU leadership presented Vision 2030 as its core stabilisation framework, reporting progress in governance, academic restructuring, improved success rates, research development and security upgrades. However, they emphasised that systemic pressures—including over‑75% reliance on NSFAS, student debt of R1.4 billion, severe accommodation shortfalls, and municipal service failures—continually exceeded institutional capacity. They appealed for a differentiated funding model and targeted infrastructure investment to sustain the University''s access mandate. The Student Representative Council (SRC) outlined acute student‑facing challenges: accommodation shortages and unsafe conditions; registration disruptions due to NSFAS delays; withholding of academic documents; unclear bursary balances; and persistent safety concerns. The Council called for urgent infrastructure intervention, improved academic administration, stronger oversight of service providers, and enhanced non‑academic support, including food security and gender‑based violence (GBV) response structures. The Institutional Forum (IF) argue', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42088/', 0),
    (42144, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-11-26', '2026 Academic Year readiness; NSFAS stabilisation; SETA appointments; with Minister', 'Video The Committee engaged with the Department of Higher Education and Training (DHET) on the 2026 Academic Year state of readiness, as well as engage the Minister on the SETA board and CEO appointments. NSFAS was also present to brief the Committee on its state of readiness for 2026 as well as on governance and stabilisation matters. SAPCO, SATVETSA, Higher Health and USAf also provided briefings although the latter could not be present. The session exposed significant systemic risks to the stability of the 2026 academic year arising from governance failures, funding delays, institutional capacity constraints, and unresolved legal and administrative weaknesses across the post-school education and training sector. The discussion underscored that the challenges confronting universities, TVET colleges, CET colleges, SETAs, and NSFAS are not isolated operational problems, but interconnected failures of planning, accountability, and execution that, if left unaddressed, are likely to result in disruption at the start of the academic year. A central concern related to the structural misalignment between academic calendars, funding flows, and student admissions processes. It was emphasised that the current approach, whereby NSFAS confirms funding only after institutions finalise course offers, risks excluding financially vulnerable students from available spaces. Institutions are compelled to allocate places to students who can afford upfront registration, while NSFAS-funded students receive confirmation after spaces have already been taken. This approach was identified as a material risk for 2026, with the potential to destabilise registration processes and exacerbate inequality. Funding flows to institutions were identified as a persistent weakness. It was noted that departmental transfers to universities are disproportionately concentrated in the fourth quarter of the financial year, undermining institutional cash flow and operational planning. NSFAS disbursements to u', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42144/', 0),
    (42212, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2025-12-03', 'NSF 2024/25 Annual Report; NSFAS 2023/24 Annual Report; Audit Outcomes', 'Video Annual Reports 2024/25 The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education met to receive a briefing from the Auditor-General of South Africa (AGSA) on recent audit outcomes and to consider the annual reports of the National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS) for 2024/25 and the National Skills Fund (NSF) for 2023/24. AGSA reported an adverse audit opinion for NSFAS and a qualified opinion for the NSF. In both cases, the audit findings pointed to serious weaknesses in financial management, performance reporting and regulatory compliance. These deficiencies were attributed to prolonged leadership instability, reliance on outdated and largely manual systems, and weak internal controls. Committee Members expressed deep concern about the ongoing governance and operational failures at both entities. Discussion centred on the NSF’s inconsistent explanations for its failure to fill critical vacancies, its continued underspending despite a clear skills development mandate, and the lack of effective consequence management for officials linked to poor audit outcomes and irregular expenditure. Members also raised serious allegations of conflicts of interest within the NSF and criticised the absence of the accounting authority and the responsible Minister from the meeting, which limited the Committee’s ability to enforce direct accountability. The NSF’s failure to conduct a tracer study for the past two years was highlighted as a significant shortcoming, leaving it unable to demonstrate the employment impact of its funded programmes. NSFAS presented a turnaround plan aimed at stabilising leadership, implementing a new loan management system and ensuring the timely closure of projects. The NSF reported that it had introduced a new digital system to address reporting weaknesses and was pursuing consequence management through external investigations. Officials from both entities acknowledged that previous reporting on recovery efforts had been overstated and that progress to date ', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42212/', 0),
    (42402, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2026-02-18', 'Employment of foreign academics at universities and colleges, with DHET Minister & DHA Deputy Minister', 'At a joint meeting of the Portfolio Committees on Higher Education and on Home Affairs, Members received briefings from the Department of Higher Education and Training and the Department of Home Affairs on the employment of foreign nationals across universities, Technical and Vocational Education and Training (TVET) colleges, and Community Education and Training (CET) colleges. According to audited data presented from the Higher Education Management Information System, South African citizens constituted 92.26% of the post-school education workforce in 2024, while foreign nationals accounted for 7.74%. The data indicated that the majority of foreign employees were concentrated in academic roles. Of the full-time foreign staff complement, 82.89% served as instructional or research professionals, with the remainder occupying administrative, technical and support positions. The Department of Higher Education and Training indicated that it was working with the Department of Home Affairs and the Department of Employment and Labour to strengthen data integrity and ensure alignment with national policy priorities. The Department emphasised that internationalisation remained a strategic component of South Africa’s higher education system, contributing to research collaboration, curriculum internationalisation, academic benchmarking and broader global competitiveness. Presentations also outlined the legislative and administrative frameworks governing the employment of foreign nationals in higher education institutions. Particular attention was given to the use of the Critical Skills List and its relevance to recommendations arising from Operation Vulindlela. However, the briefings highlighted persistent gaps in data management and interdepartmental coordination, complicating efforts to verify whether institutions consistently complied with legal requirements when appointing foreign staff. Members reported that oversight visits had revealed instances where foreign nationals oc', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42402/', 0),
    (42448, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2026-02-25', 'Implementation of the Committee’s recommendations following oversight visits at higher education institutions, with Deputy Minister', 'Video ATC251114: Report of the Portfolio Committee on Higher Education on its Oversight visit to The University of Fort Hare (UFH), Dated 12 November 2025 ATC251114: Report of the Portfolio Committee on Higher Education on Its Oversight visit to Kwazulu-Natal, Dated 12 November 2025 The Committee convened in Parliament to receive progress reports from the Department of Higher Education and Training on the implementation of recommendations arising from its week-long oversight visit to institutions in KwaZulu-Natal in October 2025, and to obtain an update on governance matters at the University of Fort Hare. The University Branch reported limited but measurable progress. At the University of Zululand, the Africa Complex residence had been decommissioned and maintenance undertaken during the holiday period. At the University of KwaZulu-Natal, the contractor responsible for the abandoned 100-bed residence project had been terminated; however, prospects for financial recovery were constrained by prescription risks. Senior counsel had advised that litigation in relation to the Oval Residence matter carried weak prospects of success. At the University of Fort Hare, structural repairs had been completed, a successful SRC election had been conducted, and the institutional Recovery Plan was reported to be on schedule. No substantive update was provided regarding the Durban University of Technology, beyond an indication that the Department remained engaged with the institution. The TVET Branch reported that written submissions and supporting documentation on uMfolozi TVET College and Elangeni TVET College had been furnished to the Secretariat. It confirmed that disciplinary and criminal proceedings were underway at Elangeni in relation to ghost employees and associated financial irregularities, and that infrastructure and student accommodation procurement processes had been reinitiated. The CET Branch advised that a targeted support plan for the KwaZulu-Natal CET College’s fin', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42448/', 0),
    (42511, 'Higher Education and Training', 64, '2026-03-04', 'Briefing by the Department of Higher Education on its Q2 and Q3 Performance and Financial Reports; with Ministry', 'ATC251105: Budgetary Review and Recommendation Report of the Portfolio Committee on Higher Education on its Assessment of the 2024/25 Annual Reports of the Department of Higher Education and Training and Entities, Dated 29 October 2025 The Portfolio Committee on Higher Education and Training received the Department of Higher Education and Training''s Second and Third Quarter Performance and Financial Report for the 2025/26 financial year. The Minister, both Deputy Ministers, the Director-General, and senior departmental officials were in attendance. Members welcomed the full attendance of the Ministry, noting this was a significant demonstration of commitment to parliamentary accountability. The Department reported that all 15 direct targets planned for the second quarter had been achieved, a result Members acknowledged as encouraging. Performance declined in the third quarter, with 14 of 17 direct targets achieved at a rate of 82%. System targets, which measure performance across 26 autonomous universities and reflect data the Department cannot fully control, were met in full in the second quarter but fell to only 7 of 18 in the third quarter, representing a 39% achievement rate. Members expressed serious concern about this systemic underperformance and called on the Department to assert its oversight mandate over institutions more confidently rather than attributing shortfalls to institutional autonomy. Infrastructure underperformance was identified as the Committee''s most urgent concern. Members placed on record a detailed pattern of near-complete financial expenditure in Programme 2 alongside deeply inadequate non-financial performance across multiple consecutive financial years. In 2023/24, Programme 2 spent 97.6% of its R1.493 billion allocation while achieving only 64% of targets. In 2024/25, it spent 99.5% of R3.704 billion while achieving only 31% of targets. Members characterised this pattern as fiscal dumping, with funds transferred to institutions in late', 'https://pmg.org.za/committee-meeting/42511/', 0),
